<http://www.isid.org>
In this update:
[1] Data on "shared mutations" among SARS virus isolates
[2] Two sequence variants from the same patient
******
[1]
Date: Thurs 24 Apr 2003
From: Henry L Niman, PhD <henry_niman@hms.harvard.edu>

Update on Shared Mutations
--------------------------
The following update on shared mutations [see: SARS - worldwide (63):
etiology 20030423.0994] has been received from Dr Henry Niman.
Yesterday I gave several examples of mutations shared between CUHK-W1 and 5
isolates from the mainland (GZ01, BJ01, BJ02, BJ03, BJ04). Since these
mutations were well conserved among mainland isolates, but not found in
other isolates linked to the Metropole Hotel, I thought that the data
supported a Metropole source containing a mixture of variants. Although
CUHK-W1 was isolated from a patient from the Prince of Wales Hospital, I
have been informed by Dennis Lo and Stephen Tsui, who were involved in the
sequencing of this isolate, that the patient was not one of the 138
patients linked to the visitor of the Metropole Hotel. This patient had
traveled to Thailand and mainland China shortly before developing SARS
symptoms, suggesting an origin outside of Hong Kong, consistent with the
shared mutations found with mainland China isolates.
In addition to the D-to-E mutation at position 5768 in orf1ab, which is
found in CUHK-W1, GZ01, BJ01, BJ02, BJ03, BJ04, there is another mutation
of a T changing to I at position 244 in E2. This amino acid is found in all
6 isolates. Thus, these 2 sets of shared mutations define 2 hot spots where
6 of the sequenced isolates have one amino acid while the other 4 have
another. This distribution raises the possibility that the true mutations
are the amino acids shared by the Tor2, Urbani, KYK, and HKU-39849
isolates. I have not yet been able to obtain the history of the HKU-39849
isolate. However, there is another shared mutation at position 577 of E2 in
which S replaces A. This mutation is found in KYK, which is from a tourist
who stayed at the Metropole Hotel. However, the mutation is shared with,
BJ01 and GZ01, isolates from the mainland. This mutation is not seen in
Tor2 or Urbani, 2 isolates closely linked to the Metropole Hotel. Thus, the
distribution of this mutation supports the notion that the infections at
the Metropole Hotel involved a number of variants. As noted above, however,
Tor2, Urbani, KYK, and HKU-39849 share amino acids found at position 5769
in orf1ab and position 244 in E2, which supports a more closely related
source of the infections at the Metropole Hotel.
These shared mutations, especially the 2 loci that are shared by the 5
mainland isolates and CUHK-W1, support an etiological role for SARS
coronavirus in SARS.
Here is the list of shared mutations:
(1) orf1ab [the putative polymerase gene]:
3047 V to A [Val to Ala] in BJ01, BJ02, BJ03, CUHK-W1
3072 V to A [Val to Ala] in CUHK-W1*
3196 A to V [Ala to Val} in BJ01, BJ02, BJ03
5768 D to E [Asp to Glu] in BJ01, BJ02, BJ03, BJ04, GZ01, CUHK-W1
(2) E2 [putative glycoprotein gene]:
77 G to D [Gly toAsp] in BJ03, CUHK-W1
244 T to I [Thr to Ile] in BJ01, BJ02, BJ03, BJ04, GZ01, CUHK-W1
577 A to S [Ala to Ser] in KYK, BJ01, GZ01
(3) N [putative nucleoprotein gene]
387 N to P [Asn to Pro] in GZ01, BJ02
* This change is only in CUHK-W1, not BJ01, BJ02, BJ03 as reported
yesterday [see: SARS - worldwide (63): etiology 20030423.0994] - the 3
Beijing isolates have a shared mutation at position 3196, which is A to V,
as well as V to A change at position 3047.
--
Henry L Niman, PhD
Department of Bioengineering
Shriners' Burn Center
51 Blossom Street, Room 422
Boston, MA 02114 USA
