******
[2]
Date: Thu 24 Apr 2003
From: Henry L Niman, PhD <henry_niman@hms.harvard.edu>

2 distinct SARS virus variants from the same patient
----------------------------------------------------
This issue of SARS mutations will likely be viewed with increased interest.
More information is now available on the 5 isolates from mainland China
<http://www.genomics.org.cn:8080/bgi/news/zhongxin/news030416-2_fasta.htm>.
One area of interest is a comparisons of mutations in 2 isolates (BJ01 and
BJ03) from the same individual. The partial data have been submitted to
Genebank, and it is possible that there are some sequencing errors, but the
data are quite strong for multiple variants in the same individual.
There are 4 mutations shared between BJ01 and BJ03. 2 of them are found in
all 5 mainland china isolates as well as CUHK-W1, and the 4 other isolates
may be the true mutations. The 2 widely shared alterations are at position
5768 in orf1ab [the putative polymerase gene] (D changing to E) and I
changing to T at position 244 in E2 [putative glycoprotein gene]. Another
mutation shared between BJ01 and BJ03 is also found in BJ02 and CUHK-W1 (V
changing to A at position 3196). This change is found in BJ02 and CUHK-W1
at position 3047 in orf1ab [the putative polymerase gene]. The fourth
change shared between BJ01 and BJ03 is also found in BJ02 (A changing to V
at position 3196 in orf1ab).
However, in addition to the 4 mutations shared between BJ01 and BJ03, each
isolate has mutations not shared. BJ01 has 3 additional mutations not
shared with the 9 other isolates. All 3 changes are in orf1ab at positions
1718 (L to W), 2230 (A to V), and 2770 (V to I). Since these changes have
not been seen elsewhere, sequencing errors remain a possibility (although
not likely).
In contrast, BJ03 also has 3 mutations not found in BJ01, but 2 of these
mutations have been found in other isolates, reducing the likelihood that
they are due to sequencing errors. The mutation unique to BJ03 is also in
orf1ab at position 3426 (V to I). Of interest are the 2 other mutations in
E2. At position 78, the change of G to D is also found in CUHK-W1, while
the A to S change at position 577 is also found in KYK and GZ01, which were
from patients in Singapore and Guangzhou, respectively.
The finding of this A to S mutation in isolates from 2 other geographically
distinct regions, but not in another isolate from the same patient, raises
issues of multiple variants within the same patient as well as tissue
tropism linked to specific amino acid changes.
--
Henry L Niman, PhD
Department of Bioengineering
Shriners' Burn Center
51 Blossom Street, Room 422
Boston, MA 02114 USA
<henry_niman@hms.harvard.edu>
[All RNA viruses by their nature are inherently highly mutable; while these
sequence comparisons of a small number of SARS coronavirus isolates are
intriguing, it is perhaps too early to speculate on the biological
significance of any of these variable sites. - Mod.CP]
